Not just theobromine. Caffeine too. To many mammals other than humans--not just carnivores, equines too, maybe others--caffeine is very poisonous. It can cause them to have seizures and heart attacks. It seems to have evolved as a plant toxin that made animals learn to avoid eating it. Theobromine, too. We think of bears and wolves as having cast iron stomachs--they eat carrion. We think of goats as eating literal garbage, though that isn't literally true in the way it's depicted in cartoons from the 20th Century. But humans eat things every day that would be very harmful to them. How much of this stuff it'd be appropriate to bring into a story of humans and anthros, I don't know. I am personally inclined to dial the toxicity aspects back because they make the reader ask too many questions, if multiple sapient species are sharing a world. Of course if the story involve dimensional portals between Earth and Parallel Earth #27 where sapient anthros evolved instead of primates, it can be a plot point.
